# eToro SSO Identity

When integrating eToro SSO, identity rules matter more than they look — getting them wrong silently corrupts your user table or leaks data between users. Read this before storing anything keyed off an eToro identity.

## 1. Never use the OIDC `sub` claim as a cross-app identity key

eToro's STS issues a per-OAuth-client **Pairwise Pseudonymous Identifier** (PPID) as the OIDC `sub` claim. The same physical eToro user receives a *different* `sub` from each STS client registration — your dev and prod environments will see different `sub` values for the same person.

**Symptoms of the mistake:**

- Users have separate accounts in dev vs. prod even though they signed in with the same eToro login.
- Migrating between OAuth clients silently splits each user's data into two records.
- "Why does this user have two portfolios?" — that's why.

## 2. Always resolve identity via `/api/v1/me`; use `gcid` as your primary key

After the OAuth token exchange, call:

```
GET /api/v1/me
Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
```

Response shape:

```json
{ "gcid": <number>, "realCid": <number>, "demoCid": <number> }
```

**All three are stable cross-app identifiers with a one-to-one relationship.** Given any one of them you can derive the other two via `/api/v1/me`. None of them rotates and none of them changes when the user signs in from a different OAuth client. The choice between them is about **role**, not safety:

- **`gcid`** — global, environment-independent identity. Recommended as the primary key on your user record (e.g. `etoro_gcid` column / claim) because it's the same value regardless of whether the user is in real or demo.
- **`realCid`** — the user's Customer ID (CID) for the real environment. **Whenever an eToro endpoint asks for a `CID` or `cidList`, it means `realCid`** (or `demoCid` in demo) — it does **not** mean `gcid`.
- **`demoCid`** — the equivalent for the demo environment.

The unsafe identifier is the OIDC `sub` claim (see §1) — not any of these three.

## 3. Pass `realCid`, never `gcid`, to `/user-info/people` (and similar CID-taking endpoints)

```
GET /user-info/people?cidList=<realCid>
```

`gcid` and `realCid` are different *numeric values* for the same user — they live in different ID namespaces. The endpoint accepts any number structurally (no validation error fires), so passing a `gcid` will silently resolve to a *different* user whose CID happens to numerically equal that `gcid` value. This is a hard-to-spot data-leak bug: the wrong user's profile comes back, with no error. Always pass `realCid` (or `demoCid` in demo) to anything that takes a `CID` / `cidList` parameter.

## 4. Refresh tokens rotate; persist the new one atomically

Every successful refresh against the eToro SSO token endpoint (with `grant_type=refresh_token`) returns a NEW refresh token; the previous one is immediately invalidated. Persist `access_token` and `refresh_token` in the same DB write — if you only update `access_token`, the next refresh will fail with `400 invalid_grant` and lock the user out.

The full token-handling playbook lives in the **`implementing-etoro-sso`** skill; what's non-negotiable here is that the new RT must be persisted, not discarded.

## 5. Refresh failure ≠ network error

A `400 invalid_grant` from the SSO token endpoint (or a `401` on a Public API call where the subsequent refresh also fails) means the session is dead — eToro has revoked it server-side. Don't retry indefinitely; surface a "Reconnect to eToro" flow that re-runs the auth-code grant against the same user record. See the **`handling-etoro-session-expiry`** skill.
